I think the horse / corvette comparison is deeply flawed.  The claim is that, since the the CO2 produced by the horse is consumed by grass, and grass transforms the CO2 into oxygen, and the oxygen is consumed by the horse, that the horse is not adding CO2 to the air.  The CO2 from the corvette can also be consumed by grass, and transformed into Oxygen.  Oxygen is an element that we do not currently have a problem with over abundance of.  However, one could argue that the Corvette uses Oxygen during the combustion process to generate energy and CO2, so the Corvette also has that same "cycle".  

Both the horse and the corvette add CO2 to the air.  The claim is also made that, given the same mileage, a horse emits more CO2 than a corvette.  What is missing here is that a horse is much slower than a corvette, and requires much more rest.  A person using a horse for transportation would likely travel much less mileage than a person with a corvette.  So, no, a horse will not typically produce more CO2 than a corvette, unless the person driving the Corvette is going extremely slow and for only a short distance.

This guy misses a few points.  First of all, the automobile IS in a CO2 / O2 cycle.  When a vehicle burns fossil fuels, it requires oxygen to combust the fuel.  That is why your vehicle has an air intake manifold.  And no matter where the CO2 comes from, it still gets absorbed by plants and turned back into oxygen.  Fact, our atmosphere is a bit more than 20% oxygen, or 200,000 parts per million.  Fact, our atmosphere is approximately 416 parts per million CO2, or about 0.0416%.  This is up from estimates 200 years ago of about 300 PPM.  So yes, we have seen a significant increase over past levels.  But as a percentage of our atmosphere, the rise is miniscule, and less than one PPM per year since the start of the industrial revolution.  What are the true effects of the rise in CO2?  We have seen a greening of the planet, meaning more forests, more tillable farmland, and greater crop yields, and may possibly increase oxygen levels over time, but levels are currently remaining nearly unchanged.  All things necessary to support a growing population.

This presentation is very selective in the information used and omits numerous other considerations to present a fairly biased viewpoint.  It doesn't consider the role that BEVs will start to play shortly in smart-grid evolution, as new features like vehicle to grid (V2G) become standard on new cars turning them all into virtual power plants. This will make BEVs pivotal in enabling faster transition to renewable energy by stabilising grid supply from otherwise unreliable generation sources, like solar and wind, making them more viable baseload generation solutions. We now have car companies like Volvo providing CO2 figures for the entire lifecycle, cradle to grave, of their ICE and BEV cars which show the BEVs are considerably lower in CO2 compared to an ICE car driven for equal distances over the life of the car. 
It has also been shown that the latest BEVs have now reached levels of efficiency that even if powered entirely from coal generated electricity, they still contribute less CO2 than an ICE car of equivalent class, driving the same distance. Granted we still couldn't push the button today anyway,  as we physically do not have the electricity generation capacity to swap every car.  But given solar and wind are now much cheaper per MWh than any other generation source, to not mandate a transition to a green energy economy with BEVs underpinning the grid would be like placing shackles around the feet of your economy.  Yes, it's going to cost to transition, but the sooner you reach that pivot point the benefit potential will be enormous.  The only people to benefit from sticking with the status quo are fossil fuel companies.

EV Charging in a condo needs to consider Demand Charges that could increase peak demand. Peak Demand from say 10 cars charging at 7 kW could increase demand charges by 70 kW if all 10 EV's were charging at the same time and during peak usage. It's a huge component of electricity bills and not always very transparent. Unico Power is working with me right now to get a system in our building here in Calgary, AB. Their system eliminates excess charging during peak demand periods with an intelligent energy management system, i.e.  only charging EV's when demand is below the peak. Even filling a parkade with dozens of wall outlets charging at the same time could increase peak demand by approx 1.5 kW per vehicle...

Depends on how many KMs you're doing - if less than 50-80, then no charger needed. Also, some legacy Tesla destination chargers will work with MG ZS EV, Ioniq, and Kona. Use plug share and check reviews. The one near me works for other brands.

Unless your HPWC is old (think I saw the new ones start appearing 2018/2019) and actually has the "legacy" mode switch then won't work with other cars(1).
Same applies for destination chargers where they have been set to legacy mode; only way to know is to check Plugshare and see if leaf or others have charged there.
If you need to charge at the increased speed for both cars could look at selling your existing charger and getting a generic one (like zappi) or get a socket installed and use a mobile 11/22kw charger wired up (like KWIK Portable Type 2 Charger | 32 Amp | 22kW) so you can use for regional super remote charging if that's kinda in your EV plans
I recommend against getting a "dual" charging unit; though slightly cheaper, if it fails your very stuck instead of partly stuck.
Note the tesla mobile charger will work if you need an emergency charger for the other car; doesn't have the limits in it.

(1) - I have seen recently (a month ago) on twitter a pic with a non tesla using a new HPWC charger; but never saw a follow up so might have been faked

Will love to know about 1. Development in infra to support a complete ev world. 2. Future of borophene 3. What measures has been taken to keep the world's battery dumping ground (Africa) clean

There is no battery ground in existence, not in Africa, not anywhere.Batteries are and have been nearly 100% recyclable. That's been case with lead acid batteries for 100 years, in case of lithium batteries , in addition to being recyclable they are also reusable after their EV usage. So after about 10-15 years of EV usage, the batteries are used as home storage or industry level energy storage for another 10 years before the materials are recycled out of them. The African problem is actually the mining problem.Cobalt is unethically extracted which is part of some of the battery chemistry. But, there are many battery chemistries that are Cobalt free and world is moving towards that. Also, that same Cobalt is used for oil refining and there is no way of refining oil without Cobalt. Development of infrastructure is a good point and it's accelerating at a rapid pace. I have a separate video on that which answers this question. Unlike other infrastructure the main part of the infrastructure is already there, which is the grid. Building a charging station is not a big deal at all. I will look into Borophene and will feature it in some future video if I find it promising.

You are right about the size being the issue with smartphone batteries. They were being recycled but only in small scale and the reuse percentage was less than 50%. Over the last couple of years almost all electronics companies(
Samsung, LG and others) have started a recycle program in almost all countries where they collect e-waste and batteries. But, that's just part of corporate welfare program and not very commercially profitable. Thanks to EV batteries, the battery recycling is becoming profitable and the estimation is that by 2025, it will be a very big and profitable business and keep on growing. Why 2025? Why not now? As of now, the first generation of EV batteries(2012 and prior) are just being put to reuse(it's called Second life), none of them have reached the stage of recycling yet. Borophene is where Graphene used to be 2 decades ago. We just had a breakthrough with graphene manufacturing last year(in lab) and we will probably see grapahene commercial manufacturing picking up gradually over this decade. Borophene has a long way to go.

the regeneration affect strictly depends on the thermal management system because the one important thing which plays a major role in battery's life is temperature. Regeneration is a process to recharge battery by converting mechanical energy into electrical energy and in recharging process obviously temperature (you need to maintain) and BMS to ensure the battery is getting evenly charged, because un even charging may lead to detoriation in life of the pack (aggressively)

Good question. Battery Cycle life is defined by say 100% DoD (depth of discharge) charging & discharging. DoD and Cycle life have nonlinear relationship. Say if a battery is 100% DoD done, battery life is 2k cycle, then the same battery if done 80% DoD (say 10%-90% SOC cycling) then life will be 4k.  Also during regeneration, only a fraction of it  chargers battery usually 15 to 20%. While this will affect the cycle life, the contribution is very negligible due to above reasons.

There is indeed a hoax associated with climate change but we need to define exactly what that hoax is.

The world is being severely damaged due to human created pollution and destruction of natural environments.  These things are quite obvious and can be traced back to human overpopulation.  The hypothesis of anthropogenic (i.e. human caused) climate change has no hard evidence to support it. Hang on though, isn't the climate changing?  Can't we see changes in climatic condition s in various places across the planet?  Indeed we do see changes in the climate but let's examine the nature of those changes.


The problem with the concept of anthropogenic climate change is that proponents consider only a few decades in their personal experience of the climate in their locality and then conclude that what they have experienced during their lifetime constitutes ‚Äònormal‚Äô climatic conditions.  They then interpret any deviation from that supposed ‚Äònormal‚Äô climate as evidence of supposed anthropogenic climate change.

However the current climate, over all regions of the Earth, has been drastically different at varying times in the Earth's history. The coldest portion of the last glacial period began about 110,000 years ago and a warming period began about 12,000 years ago. Thus, for 98,000 of the past 110,000 years, the ‚Äònormal‚Äô or ‚Äòtypical‚Äô climate consisted of as much as 30% of the Earth‚Äôs surface being covered with ice.  The ice sheets covered vast areas of Europe, North America, and Asia; up to three kilometers thick in some locations, with the ice completely covering Canada and as far south as current day London, England.
	
Ref:  https://donsmaps.com/icemaps.html
Ref:  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Last_Glacial_Period

Note also that there were forests and abundant animal life in the Antarctic during the Cretaceous period which ran from 145 to 66 million years ago.

Ref:  https://www.bbcearth.com/blog/?article=when-dinosaurs-roamed-antarctica

The Earth has been much warmer and much colder at various times in its history long before the human race even existed as a species, let alone as a technological species.  Our ephemeral existence is not long enough to determine what is ‚Äònormal‚Äô or ‚Äòtypical‚Äô for the Earth's climate.  Note that the human race has only been keeping climate records since about the year 1850 and what we know of climate over geological time spans comes from scientific study of the matter via geological evidence and samples of Antarctic ice and not from direct observation.

Ref: http://www.bgs.ac.uk/discoveringGeology/geologyOfBritain/iceAge/home.html

Read the articles cited above and get a grasp of the length of time involved in geological time spans. The entire history of the human race is but a blink of an eye in comparison with the age of the Earth and the climatic changes it has seen.  What any of us have personally observed in our lifetimes can in no way be described as a ‚Äònormal‚Äô or ‚Äòtypical‚Äô climate for the Earth throughout its extremely long history.  The Earth's climate has always changed and those changes have been as a result of natural processes.  The climate is still changing and will in fact always be changing but to conclude that such changes can only and solely be due to human activities is not a conclusion that fits the facts.

Rather than the false flag of supposed human caused ‚Äòclimate change‚Äô, we should be concerned with environmental pollution, environmental destruction and overpopulation.  Those are the factors that put the human race and the planetary environment at risk.  The best thing we could do as a species right now is to reduce the human population by using the very effective methods we have available for birth control.  A smaller population would result in less resources consumed and less environmental pollution.  For those who still believe that there is such a thing as anthropogenic (human caused) ‚Äòglobal warming‚Äô or ‚Äòglobal climate change‚Äô, a smaller population would mean less resources of all kinds being consumed and consequently less ‚Äògreenhouse gases‚Äô.  Generating the energy required for our society to function by using more ecologically friendly systems to do so would also be extremely helpful and kinder to the environment.

Note well that over the last 100 years the human population has grown from about 1.5 billion to about 8 billion people, an increase of over 530%.  Breeding more and more human beings at such a rate cannot go on forever due to the consequent stress on the environment.  The inevitable consequence of unlimited population growth will be insufficient resources to provide sufficient food for an overly large population and an unlivable environment poisoned with toxic wastes.

Secret #2: The rental rate may not always be as attractive as going through broker, but usually T&C are much more relaxed and prices of additional equipment and services are much lower. Depending on Your needs, renting directly through provider can be cheaper. Rental companies have their own reservation teams, don't be afraid to ask them anything, email is the best way of communication.

Secret #5: Third party insurance (bought on broker's/TA's website) will only cover You AFTER You pay for the excess, and depending on Your rate, it can be up to vehicle's full cost! Also, not before they get all of the documentation from the rental company, and sometimes that documentation - like police reports, take up to a year to obtain, depending on country.

My general advice - always book as early as You can and don't fall for the rental price alone. Read T&C and compare prices of additional equipment and services. Doesn't matter if You've booked through broker (rentalcars, kayak, etc) or directly with rental company, always communicate with the end provider to have written proof of all of the rates, and services You're not obliged to pay.

As someone who worked for Enterprise in an airport. 1) Only some of the counter people make commission. As a customer service agent yes under Alamo and National(both owned by Enterprise) but as an Management Trainee or higher position we do not make commission at all however we do need a certain percentage of tickets to qualify at the end if the month. 2) I recommend renting through the actual website only because I had at least 10ppl a day have some kind of travel issue or problem with the reservation and we could not do much on our end, they had to crawl thru hoops calling the 3rd parties they booked for to get anything fixed, they also don't always tell you or inform of some other fees such as a local security deposits or policies that might require additional documentation that can prevent someone from getting a vehicle depending on the location. 3) At least with Enterprise the prepaid fuel is cheaper than any of the gas stations with a 10mile radius of the airport by at least 15cents as we have someone who daily checks the flutuations of the gas market and adjust our area accordingly. 4)The National emerald club is definitely worth it in certain locations like Atlanta and Las Vegas as you do get a different selection of vehicles higher in the ranks while only paying for the midsized car rate. For example a Camaro SS for the price of a Corolla and the program is free. Also depending on the location and number of available cars Emerald club members were given priority to available vehicles, by some employees, they also get the newest sometimes straight off the truck vehicles with 5 miles, and free upgrades to luxury vehicles

When it comes to prepaid fuel, it's best to buy it if you're off airport and returning to an airport. Fuel near off airport is cheaper than it will be when you get to the airport. If you have the car for several days, in 2022, you never know what the gas prices will be like next week. So if you prepaid for the fuel, you got a deal if price shoots up again. Especially during holidays.

In regards to 3rd party insurance, I work for Hertz, and I can promise that our Loss Damage Waiver (LDW) is a much better option than that $10.99 Collision Damage Waiver (CDW) and here is why. Our LDW will cover the rental car 100%, bumper to bumper, regardless of fault, with a zero deductible, including theft. There is a reason the CDW is  called a COLLISION damage Waiver. It only protects you in the event of a collision. Maybe theft. But is usually does not cover 100% of the vehicle. And you personal insurance will only cover up to the amount in your policy. So if your policy covers $25000 and you rent a $80000 suv, if you total that suv, you're responsible for that remaining $55000 out of pocket. It's always best to take our LDW if your traveling far, poor weather, in a college/party town, during major travel/holiday seasons, or when in an unfamiliar area.

So, I've got a quick, useful story to add regarding credit card coverage (collision damage waiver). I am American, but I live and work overseas. While visiting family in the States, I rented a car at LAX and used one of my Bank of America Visa credit cards to pay for it. It had the collision damage waiver benefit for rental cars, so I didn't get any additional insurance on top of that. The following day, in rural California, I hit a deer that suddenly ran onto the freeway. Fortunately we were all safe in the vehicle, but the front of the car was an absolute mess. Very long story short, I eventually received a bill from a collections company for well over $10k!! (The car had likely been written off/ auctioned off.) After months of talking with Visa's Card Benefits Services and sending all types of paperwork and documentation,  Visa negotiated a settlement with the collections agency, and I ended up paying $0! In fact, I was surprised to learn that Visa's fine print (for my specific card) even permitted me to receive full reimbursement for the towing charges I had paid out of pocket the day of the accident ($250+). Obviously,  I was tremendously grateful. All the fine print for my card ended up working in my favor in this specific situation. Here are lessons I learned  that I will pass on to you: Read the fine print of the benefits that come with your specific card!!! Find out if there are limits to coverage, such as the number of days you'll be renting a car AND type of coverage offered by the card (secondary or primary). Check on coverage for domestic rentals vs. international rentals. If you accept any insurance from the rental car company or a third party (which I am not discouraging whatsoever here), just be aware that your credit card benefit might not cover you in the same way. Obviously,  I'm very fortunate nobody was hurt AND no other vehicles or people were involved in the accident. That certainly could have changed the financial outcome dramatically. Again, read the fine print... I'd even encourage you to take ten minutes to call your Card Benefit Services to ask questions about the coverage they provide.

So I know this video is getting a little old and if I‚Äôm upfront I use to mange a very highly reputable car rental location in an airport. Some tips for your next video:
1. Insurance is worth the cost if you are taking the car a far distance and or thru a place with more intense weather climates such as snow. You are not liable for any damage and it saves people a lot of hassle. 
2. Booking thru 3rd party‚Äôs will often go off without a hitch, no doubt, find your deals, but by doing this, you are not guaranteed a car and if you buy their 3rd party insurance, the car rental company will contact you and not the third party insurance. you are made a middle man to get the car fixed. I have seen many of people become very frustrated with the process.
3. A lot of rental systems will register an error and a manager will be involved if too many discounts are being applied. The counter should be able to override it for customer service reasons, but when it comes to making money, they will make you pay the difference and tell you to book straight thru the company website next time to get a more accurate price. Again, the company does not have to adhere to the price of your third party booking. And if you have a problem with that, they will tell you to contact that third party, only for you to then get lucky enough to get a refund from said third party and pay the normal rental price anyway. 
4. As he says at the end, ALWAYS get a receipt when you return the car. It is the job of the rental company to add fees before you leave and it is illegal for them to add anything after the rental is fully returned so get your proof.
Ps. You should see that 200 dollar extra processing hold on your card released back within a week and call your bank if it‚Äôs not. If you call the rental company about it, they will just tell you to call the bank because it gets released from the systems the next calendar day after return.

Disclaimer. I am a former car rental manager. On several websites I have given my assistance to people in finding the best deal. I have even consulted with the owner of Autoslash when he was first starting. And I have the emails to prove it. Overall, your six tips were 100% spot on. I do have a 7th for you. Yes, you will always save money by prepaying for a rental. And yes, rental agents do make much of their money from add-ons. But there are some add-ons that have value, and there are some ways that rental agents make money that you didn't mention. Let me go through my number seven for you. 

Car rental agents make money from walk-ups as well. I left the car rental industry in 2007. And since then I have never paid a car rental at the lowest advertised rate utilizing any of the websites. I have beaten it, often significantly.  This also works to get a better class of car than you paid for as well.

 I have this process: I book the lowest refundable rate I can find. I make sure that it's 100% refundable and that I will not have any issues if I no-show. Then when I land, with a printed copy of my rate, I will walk to all the rental companies located on the airport. I will walk up to the agent and say "can you beat this?" 95% of the time I will get an agent that will find me a cheaper rate because that walk up traffic is a commission walking out the door.  Now this will not work if you have a reservation and you try to walk up to the same company that you hold a reservation for. So you need to make sure you have one safety reservation is what I call it at a rate that you can live with. Let's say that company is Avis. When you arrive at the airport you check Hertz, national, Alamo, advantage, Fox, budget or any other rental car company to see if they can beat that rate. If they don't, you stick with your safety reservation. If they do, and almost every single time they do at least give you added value for the same price, you can opt to stay or take the better rate. 

The 5% of the time that I do not get a better rate or get the same rate, it's because they are sold out in the entire airport, which is all too common right now.  However in Las Vegas in early May, I was able to secure a rate $15 per day less than my reservation with this same process. 

There is one circumstance where using the website of the rental company is useful. If the company that you work for or the association that you are a member of has a discount, you need to at least investigate what that discount will get you. For example, if you need to pay for a second driver, many discounts will make that second driver free, include collision damage waiver insurance, include a free tank of gas, or provide other benefits on top of a discount. Your mileage may quite literally vary, but if you pay $15 a day more using a company rate then auto slash can give you, but it includes full insurance, additional drivers, it allows you a free tank of gas, you might very well come out significantly ahead. For example, it's been many years but there was a marketing company that had a negotiated rate with the company that I worked for. LDW first $5,000 was covered by the company rate, additional drivers were free, the rate also allowed the use of a debit card without additional fees, also allowed underage drivers without an additional fee. To top it all off, the rate also allowed them to return the gas at any level with no charge. But they were paying a flat $50 per day unlimited mileage. In some cities, New York for example, $50 per day at that time was fantastic. But in the off season in Hawaii, cars could be had as cheap as $15 per day. But an additional driver, underage driver, insurance would add $75 per day, you can see where the company and anyone using that code who was authorized could significantly save money.

I don't rent cars often but when I do, I take pictures of the odometer and the inside and exterior of the car when I return it.  If you go to pick-up the car, check it for damages and cleanliness, if you see ANYTHING not recorded on the contract, notify the desk of the damage and photograph it make sure it's documented.  If you will be picking it up or returning it in the dark a flashlight to check for damages is a good idea, your phone has a good one.  New damage may have been done since the last return by another driver in the lot or even the person who moved it around in the lot or filled the tank.  Better to have pictures to delete later than to have damage you have to pay for.   One last thing, check the trunk, and under the seats for trash, last time I renter there was some trash in both places.  $1.00 or 2 at a car wash vacuum is much less than they will charge you.
BTW these apply to trailers or vans rented for moving.

‚Äã@@KevinLin145 Hi Kevin, you are correct; the Charge Point charging unit, at least in some configurations, can be unplugged and removed (i.e. stolen). Of course this implies that you have the "plug-in" model charging unit (which comes with an actual "plug"), and not the "hardwired" model. (Apologies if this is too obvious and repetitive). Our county requires that a car charger be installed/powered in the following way: a new 220v circuit running from your circuit box, to and through the outside wall near the proposed location of the charging unit. Where the power line comes through the outside wall there will be a new small electrical box that houses a shut-off switch. The power line runs through and out of that shut off box and into a second, slightly smaller box that contains a 220v outlet. The third item, the charging unit, is installed next to this outlet box. The cord on the charging unit plugs into the outlet box. 
1)The Charger is now operational, and, although it seems unlikely in most residential situations, anyone with the correct port on their car can now use that charging unit to power their car battery.That can be prevented by turning off the power; either at the 220v breaker inside the household circuit box, or at the shut off box on the outside wall. This would probably be ok for occasional use, but I have heard that these switches are not really intended, nor built for, daily use. The exterior shut off box also has a protruding "staple" (of "hasp and staple") for using with a padlock. Other than shutting off the power manually, there may be some possibility that one can use the Charge Point App to restrict charging to a specific vehicle, and/or deactivate the charger between uses by that vehicle. I do not use the app, so... this is not something I can confirm.
2) Theft: yes, this charging unit can be stolen by unplugging it from the exterior 220v outlet and unmounting the charging unit from the wall But that unmounting might be a bit of a challenge. Another option: the outlet box will have several holes that are designed to be used like a staple,  i.e. you can instal a padlock which will prevent the "door" on the outlet box from being opened and the plug inside from being disconnected. Of course, padlocks are not a perfect solution, but they may provide some peace of mind.
I hope some of this has been helpful.

7:15 There are so many misconceptions about what it means to "tax the rich". 

1. Even if you could apply a 70% tax and bring in an extra $170 billion per year that would only account for 3% of the $4.9 trillion total tax revenue the government already collects each year.
2. One of the reasons most of the billionaires live in the United States is *because* of the low tax rate. If they raised the tax rate all the billionaires would leave.
3. Most billionaires got that way by providing valueable goods and services to the world and they reinvested their profits back into their companies. This means their wealth is *not* in cash. It's tied up in the share price of their stock and properties. To pay the tax they'd literally have to sell their company.
4. The way the rich avoid paying tax is by *not taking income* in the first place. No income, means no tax. How do they live?  They borrow against their assets and live off the loan.
5. Assuming you could somehow make them pay 70% of their profits in tax, that money is now gone with no productive return and can't be used to reinvest into the business. Employees would lose jobs. Their stock valuations would crash. They would have to raise their prices. All these things would have a flow on effect in the global economy.
6. Even if you combine ALL of the worlds billionaires total net worth it still only adds up to about $12.7 trillion. The US government debt is currently $31 trillion.  That's more than twice number in total debt.

Don't get me wrong, the system is rigged and unfair, but it's not as simple as you think.

We spoke to industry contacts and this is what they told us
=====
Plastic moulds are very well made in India and many 2W OEM started producing them locally, if produced locally they will be cheaper than import. However  Biggest issue is - it require first expertise and money - for design of shape (style), engineering of shape, developing of mould ( or tool). It is injection mould- which is expensive.¬†
For one 2W- expenses could be @5-10Cr.
Many OEM don't have confidence in there product - hence don't take risk to invest @10Cr in tool and some few more Cr in design and validation.
In India many supplier have injection molding machines, issue is upfront investment design and development.

=====
Another Opinion from an EV manufacturer
We have many plastic injection mould factories in India
the issue will be high quality painting factories
for example in China. .the plastic injection moulding factory will have big scale painting factory very neary by to it
We have given orders to 4 different vendors including the die cost for ABS plastic parts.. for same components 4 different vendors
all four are equally struggling for the raw materials and as well as identifying the near by painting factories who can meet the surface finish, quality and other parameters.
But we cannot give up, we will keep trying with these vendors.

I'm rather skeptical about EV's in general. Here in the UK (and much of Europe) we tend to travel relatively short distances and you're never far from a town or City, but when I look at the cost of buying an electric car it's WAY beyond my normal budget. The car I've got now cost me ¬£7,800 which is the most I have EVER spent on a car; my last car was ¬£3,500 (5 years of driving without trouble, and I sold it only because it was looking shabby) the one before that was ¬£1,600 and the one before that was ¬£900. 

I don't mind  a couple of dings and scratches on a car so I'd be happy enough buying a used EV, but regardless of cosmetics, the big thing about any EV is the _battery._ It loses range as it ages. Sure, from new it might - I'll pick on the Nissan Leaf for the sake or argument - as Nissan claims of the Nissan Leaf be good for 100,000 miles, but it will lose about 1/3rd of it's range long before that; and the Nissan Leaf doesn't exactly have long range to start with - around 90 miles on a full charge. Okay, that'll easily get me to work and back, but what about when the car is a little older? I commute 20 miles each way to work; I _should_ be okay on a 60 mile range, but it only leaves me 20 miles to spare so I'd better hope I don't have to take a diversion or I need to take the car out again the same day. 

The Nissan Leaf without a subsidy costs ¬£26,000 for the most basic short-range model. ¬£26,000? That's an awful of money. I'm spending maybe ¬£1200 per year on fuel (plus oil - another ¬£100 or so) so over 10 years I'd save - ignoring the cost of charging an EV - ¬£12,000. So we can call the real price of the EV ¬£14,000. That's still ¬£10,000 more than I would spend on a vehicle and I would not be able to trust it to get me to work when it was over 7 years old. I wonder what the resale value is on a 10 year old EV? 

If I HAD to buy an electric car today, I could do it, but it would wipe out my meager finances and I don't know how I'd afford one in the future. 

I also wonder about the true costs if and when EV's take over. I think EV fanboys are deluding themselves that the cost of charging an EV will remain cheap. If the Government can't recoup the massive tax revenues of petrol and diesel directly from EV's, they'll take it from us indirectly. To do an apples to apples comparison, petrol in the UK in 2015 was 32.4p per litre before tax and ¬£1.08 after tax. https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2979083/Britain-one-lowest-petrol-prices-Europe-tax-highest-VAT-duty-added.html
About 65% of the cost is tax. 

Is there ANY chance the Government won't want that money? They'll take it by hook or by crook. 

I don't want to rain on EV's too much; ICE cars have all kinds of practical issues too, and I am hoping that EV's become affordable - the same price as ICE cars. But I don't see how batteries will ever be cheap enough unless a whole new futuristic technology is developed.

@@RichPakistan Main Points of EV Policy (4-Wheelers):

Following are the main points of EV Policy (4-Wheelers):

    The new policy will remain in force till June 30, 2026.
    There will be 1% Customs Duty (CD), no Additional Custom Duty (ACD) or Regulatory Duty (RD) or Value Added Tax (VAT) on EV specific parts for Completely Knocked Down (CKD) units.
    There will be 25% CD, and zero ACD or RD on Completely Built Units (CBUs) import.
    Duty-Free import of plant and machinery for EV 4-Wheelers.
    Every Company can import 100 CBUs with 50% CD.
    1% CD on EV Chargers.
    Import of CKD in small cars and sport utility with 50kWh battery or below, and Light Commercial Vehicles (LCVs) with 150kWh battery would be exempted from Sales Tax, and VAT on imports, but with 1% Sales Tax on Sales. 
    No Federal Excise Duty (FED) on Electric Vehicles
    Toll Tax on National Highways (NHA) would be 50% for EVs
    Special Window at State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) for EV car financing at reduced rates
    The federal government will request provincial governments to exempt EVs from Registration Fee and Annual Renewal Token.
